  "prompt": "How early should I start ACT prep?",
  "response": "The ideal time to start preparing for the ACT depends on your current skill level, goals, and schedule. A general recommendation is to begin studying about three to six months before your test date. Here\u2019s a timeline to help you plan:\n\n1. **Three to Six Months Before the Test:**\n   - **Assessment:** Take a practice test to identify your strengths and areas that need improvement.\n   - **Planning:** Develop a study schedule based on your assessment and goals.\n   - **Resources:** Gather prep materials such as prep books, online courses, or consider enrolling in a prep class.\n\n2. **Two to Three Months Before the Test:**\n   - **Focused Study:** Spend more time on areas where you need improvement.\n   - **Practice Tests:** Take full-length practice tests under timed conditions to get used to the test format and timing.\n\n3. **One Month Before the Test:**\n   - **Review:** Go over key concepts, formulas, and strategies.\n   - **Practice:** Continue taking practice tests and review the results to fine-tune your preparation.\n\n4. **One to Two Weeks Before the Test:**\n   - **Final Review:** Focus on areas where you can make the most gains.\n   - **Relaxation:** Ensure you\u2019re well-rested and manage stress levels.\n\nAdjust the timeline based on your confidence with the material. If you are already strong in standardized testing, a shorter prep time might suffice. Conversely, if you need significant improvement, starting earlier would be beneficial.",
